    "result": {"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Sarang Joshi's Website","author":"Sarang Joshi"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"f06813ae-3480-50f9-bcfe-c2ff70116c8d","excerpt":"Windows development is a mess. Here are some of my notes to explain how it all works together as part of my crusade to not use a Mac as a software developer at…","html":"<p>Windows development is a mess. Here are some of my notes to explain how it all works together as part of my crusade to not use a Mac as a software developer at Illumio.</p>\n<h1 id=\"shells\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#shells\" aria-label=\"shells permalink\" class=\"visible-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Shells</h1>\n<h2 id=\"native\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#native\" aria-label=\"native permalink\" class=\"visible-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Native</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">cmd</code> – the most primitive command line application on Windows, pretty much obsolete</li>\n<li><code class=\"language-text\">powershell</code> – native MSFT improvement on CMD, still clunky and not POSIX compliant by a long shot. but is now cross-platform, so they’re trying for compatibility</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"unix-like\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#unix-like\" aria-label=\"unix like permalink\" class=\"visible-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Unix-like</h2>\n<p>Assists with building of native Windows applications using MinGW-w64</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.mingw.org/wiki/MSYS\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">MSYS</a> – part of MinGW, ported from Cygwin 1.3</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://msys2.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">MSYS2</a> – independent improvement on MSYS\n<ul>\n<li>includes <code class=\"language-text\">pacman</code> package manager</li>\n<li>based on Cygwin, builds on the Cygwin DLL</li>\n<li>also based on minGW-w64</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h1 id=\"compiler-toolchains-for-windows\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#compiler-toolchains-for-windows\" aria-label=\"compiler toolchains for windows permalink\" class=\"visible-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Compiler toolchains for Windows</h1>\n<p>Programs that provide native POSIX-y (need to confirm this) compilation tools, most importantly <strong>GCC</strong>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://mingw.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">MinGW</a> - stands for “minimalistic GNU for Windows”, first effort, development dropped off</li>\n<li><a href=\"http://mingw-w64.org\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">MinGW-w64</a> – improvements on MinGW for 64bit systems and Objective-C, de facto for GCC on Windows</li>\n</ul>\n<h1 id=\"terminal-emulators\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#terminal-emulators\" aria-label=\"terminal emulators permalink\" class=\"visible-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Terminal emulators</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://mintty.github.io/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">mintty</a> - the main terminal emulator for Cygwin, MSYS, MSYS2</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://conemu.github.io/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">ConEmu</a> - an alternative <strong>con</strong>sole <strong>emu</strong>lator</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/mintty/wsltty\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">wsltty</a> - Mintty designed to be used as a frontend terminal for WSL</li>\n</ul>\n<h1 id=\"linux-distributions\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#linux-distributions\" aria-label=\"linux distributions permalink\" class=\"visible-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Linux distributions</h1>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://cygwin.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">Cygwin</a>\n<ul>\n<li>distribution of open source + GNU tools, rewritten for Windows.</li>\n<li>Provides a library that has POSIX system calls expected by programs written for Linux, but can’t run native Linux binaries, i.e. a POSIX compatibility layer: <code class=\"language-text\">cygwin1.dll</code></li>\n<li>Source code written for Linux can now be compiled for Windows without major code changes, with the Cygwin library</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/about\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">WSL</a> - allows running native Linux binaries directly\n<ul>\n<li>Provides a kernel-level translation subsystem (<code class=\"language-text\">lxss</code>) to convert Linux system calls into native Windows system calls, and also translates the response back up to the linux process</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>","fields":{"readingTime":{"text":"2 min read"}},"frontmatter":{"title":"Developing Software on Windows","date":"November 16, 2018"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/tech/windows/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/tech/dev-env-setup/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Development Environment Setup"}},"next":null}},
